                <head>160. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On July 6 the Operations Coordinating Board conducted its semiannual appraisal of
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 5805/1 (see <ref target="#d120"
                        >Documents 120</ref> and <ref target="#d122">122</ref>). The Board concurred
                    in the recommendation that no policy review by the <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> was necessary at this time and that there were no developments
                    of such significance as to warrant sending a report to the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>. In line with a Presidential directive to the
                        <gloss target="#t_OCB1">OCB</gloss> to bring all <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> policy papers into “a current condition for the next
                    Administration” (<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Action No. 2215–c, approved
                    by the President on April 9; Department of State, <gloss target="#t_SS1"
                        >S/S</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> (Miscellaneous) Files: Lot
                    66 <gloss target="#t_D1">D</gloss> 95, Records of Action by the National
                    Security Council), the <gloss target="#t_OCB1">OCB</gloss> requested that the
                    Department of State prepare a draft revision of <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> 5805/1. (Memorandum by Bromley Smith, July 13; <hi
                        rend="italic">Ibid</hi>., <gloss target="#t_OCB1">OCB</gloss> Files: Lot 62
                        <gloss target="#t_D1">D</gloss> 430, Yugoslavia)</p>
            </div>
